```OCaml D2 (line 1878-1879):


The OCaml implementation for AIM_BEHIND only performs the move towards segment center effect but is missing the velocity zeroing that happens in the C version. In C, when the robot collides heavily in this mode, all three velocity components get set to zero, but the OCaml code doesn't include this behavior. I'm also noticing the same pattern might be missing in the AIM_RUN_FROM_OBJECT case as well. I'm realizing the velocity zeroing happens through different mechanisms in C versus OCaml. In C, the Move_towards_segment_center effect modifies velocity, then the code explicitly zeros it afterward. But in OCaml, there's no explicit zeroing step after the effect is performed, so the velocity modification from the C side isn't being counteracted the same way. So the velocity zeroing happens inline in C's do_ai_frame after the move effect, but in OCaml there's no corresponding step to zero out velocity after calling Move_towards_segment_center. The question is whether this discrepancy actually affects behavior — I need to trace through what the bridge returns and how the velocity gets used downstream. aml do_ai_frame returns a packed array of ai_local/ai_static fields. It doesn't return velocity. The velocity is a property of the object, not AI state.

So in C's do_ai_frame, the velocity zeroing modifies the object directly. In OCaml's do_ai_frame, the velocity is NOT modified because:
1. OCaml doesn't have access to the velocity fields
2. The velocity isn't part of what do_ai_frame returns
3. The Move_towards_segment_center effect modifies velocity in C, but then C would need to also zero it

So this IS a bug — but fixing it would require either:
A. Adding a new effect (Zero_velocity or similar) — but the rules say I can't modify bridge files
B. Somehow incorporating velocity into the do_ai_frame result — also bridge changes

Wait, let me reconsider what the bridge actually writes back from do_ai_frame. I should check whether velocity fields are included in the state that gets written back to the object.

